"""Physics (I) is a foundational course designed for first-year mechanical engineering students. This course provides an introduction to the fundamental principles of physics and their applications in mechanical engineering. The course covers topics such as mechanics, thermodynamics, waves, and optics.

Students will learn about the laws of motion, forces, energy, and momentum, and how they apply to mechanical systems. They will also study the behavior of gases, liquids, and solids, and the principles of heat transfer. The course will also cover the properties of waves, including sound and light, and their applications in engineering.

Throughout the course, students will engage in hands-on activities and experiments to reinforce their understanding of the concepts covered. They will also develop problem-solving skills through the application of physics principles to real-world engineering problems.

Upon completion of this course, students will have a solid foundation in physics and be able to apply their knowledge to the design and analysis of mechanical systems. They will also be prepared for further study in advanced physics courses and their applications in mechanical engineering."""

"""Digital Image Processing and Application is a course designed for 4th Year Electrical Engineering students who are interested in learning about the fundamentals of digital image processing and its applications. The course will cover the basic concepts of image processing, including image acquisition, image enhancement, image restoration, image segmentation, and image compression. 

The course will also focus on the practical applications of digital image processing in various fields, such as medical imaging, remote sensing, and computer vision. Students will learn how to use various software tools and programming languages, such as MATLAB, Python, and OpenCV, to implement digital image processing algorithms and analyze the results. 

Throughout the course, students will work on several projects that involve real-world applications of digital image processing. These projects will help students develop their problem-solving skills and gain hands-on experience in applying digital image processing techniques to solve real-world problems. 

By the end of the course, students will have a solid understanding of the principles of digital image processing and its applications. They will be able to apply their knowledge to solve complex problems in various fields and will be well-prepared for careers in industries such as medical imaging, robotics, and computer vision."""

"""Course Description:

Machine Learning is a graduate-level course designed for Masters Degree CSIE students who are interested in exploring the field of artificial intelligence and its applications. This course provides an in-depth understanding of the fundamental concepts, algorithms, and techniques used in machine learning.

The course begins with an introduction to the basics of machine learning, including supervised and unsupervised learning, regression, classification, clustering, and dimensionality reduction. Students will learn how to use various machine learning algorithms such as decision trees, random forests, support vector machines, and neural networks to solve real-world problems.

The course also covers advanced topics such as deep learning, reinforcement learning, and natural language processing. Students will learn how to use deep learning techniques to build complex neural networks for image recognition, speech recognition, and natural language processing.

Throughout the course, students will work on several hands-on projects and assignments to gain practical experience in implementing machine learning algorithms. They will also learn how to evaluate the performance of machine learning models and how to optimize them for better accuracy.

By the end of this course, students will have a solid understanding of the principles and techniques of machine learning and will be able to apply them to solve real-world problems. They will also be well-prepared to pursue further research in the field of artificial intelligence."""

"""Course Description:

This course is designed to provide 3rd year international business students with a comprehensive understanding of business ethics and its importance in the global business environment. The course will explore the ethical challenges that businesses face in today's world and how they can be addressed through ethical decision-making processes.

The course will cover a range of topics including the history and evolution of business ethics, ethical theories and frameworks, corporate social responsibility, sustainability, and ethical leadership. Students will also learn about the legal and regulatory frameworks that govern business ethics and the role of international organizations in promoting ethical business practices.

Through case studies, group discussions, and individual assignments, students will develop critical thinking skills and learn how to apply ethical principles to real-world business scenarios. They will also learn how to identify and manage ethical risks and conflicts in the workplace.

Upon completion of this course, students will have a deep understanding of the importance of business ethics in the global business environment and be equipped with the skills and knowledge to make ethical decisions in their future careers."""

The class is advanced precision machinery. Within the course curriculumn students need to learn about the basic concepts of precision machinery and it's use and application in the realworld/industry. The course is for 15 weeks and will be for graduate engineering students. In the first 5 weeks topics should cover the basis of precision machinery and any information and terms necessary to understand the concepts and applications. The next 5 weeks will cover the applications of precision machinery. This will give more detail into types of machinery that require precision machinery, how the movements of the machinery is done. The last 5 weeks will cover computer applications like Labview that can be used to manipulate precision machinery. Each week will give some information about it's use along with examples of the application and results. Eg the lab view program tells the robotic arm to pick up an object and move it to another place.

"Applied Artificial Intelligence" is a dynamic course designed for third-year Computer Science students, focusing on practical AI applications and real-world problem-solving. Students will explore key AI concepts, including machine learning, neural networks, natural language processing, and computer vision. Through hands-on projects, case studies, and collaborative labs, learners will develop skills in designing, implementing, and optimizing AI models. The course also covers ethical considerations and the societal impact of AI technologies. By the end, students will be equipped to tackle complex AI challenges and contribute to innovative solutions in various industries.

"Branding Design" is an advanced course tailored for Master's Degree students in Visual Communication Design. This course delves into the strategic and creative processes of building and managing compelling brand identities. Students will explore key concepts such as brand strategy, visual identity systems, logo design, typography, color theory, and brand storytelling. Through hands-on projects and critical analysis, students will develop the skills to create cohesive and impactful brand experiences across various media. By the end of the course, students will be equipped to design and implement effective branding solutions that resonate with target audiences and drive business success.
Course Details.Target Students: Master's Degree  Student in Visual Communication Design

Course Details.Course Description: "Backend Web Development" is a capstone course designed for 4th year BS Information Technology students to master server-side programming. This course covers essential backend technologies, including server architecture, database management, API development, and security protocols. Students will gain hands-on experience with languages such as Node.js, Python, or PHP, and frameworks like Express or Django. Through project-based learning, participants will develop scalable and secure web applications, integrating front-end interfaces with robust backend systems. By the end of the course, students will be equipped to design, implement, and maintain complex web services, preparing them for advanced roles in the tech industry.

"AI In Healthcare" is an advanced course designed for 4th Year Computer Science students, focusing on the transformative role of artificial intelligence in the medical field. Students will explore machine learning algorithms, natural language processing, and computer vision applications in diagnostics, treatment planning, and patient management. The course integrates theoretical knowledge with practical case studies, ethical considerations, and hands-on projects, enabling students to develop innovative AI solutions for real-world healthcare challenges. By the end of the course, students will be equipped to contribute to the advancement of AI-driven healthcare technologies.

"Prompt Engineering for Creatives" is a dynamic course tailored for 3rd Year Marketing students, focusing on harnessing AI-driven tools to enhance creative processes. Students will explore techniques for crafting effective prompts to generate compelling content, from ad copy to social media posts. The curriculum covers AI fundamentals, prompt optimization, and ethical considerations. Through hands-on projects and real-world case studies, learners will develop the skills to integrate AI seamlessly into their marketing strategies, driving innovation and efficiency. This course empowers future marketers to leverage cutting-edge technology for creative excellence.

"Large Language Models" is an advanced course designed for 4th Year BS Computer Science students, focusing on the theory, architecture, and applications of large-scale language models like GPT-3. Students will explore natural language processing (NLP) fundamentals, model training techniques, and ethical considerations. The course includes hands-on projects to build, fine-tune, and deploy language models, enabling students to develop practical skills in AI-driven text generation, sentiment analysis, and conversational agents. By the end of the course, students will be proficient in leveraging large language models to solve complex language-related challenges.

"Generative AI" is a cutting-edge course designed for 2nd Year Computer Science students, focusing on the principles and applications of generative models in artificial intelligence. Students will explore key concepts such as neural networks, deep learning, and probabilistic models, with hands-on experience in creating AI systems capable of producing original content, such as text, images, and music. The course covers state-of-the-art techniques including GANs (Generative Adversarial Networks) and VAEs (Variational Autoencoders). By the end of the course, students will have a solid understanding of generative AI and its potential to innovate various industries.

"Course Description:

Business Calculus is a course designed for 2nd Year Business Students who want to develop their mathematical skills and apply them to real-world business problems. This course will introduce students to the fundamental concepts of calculus, including limits, derivatives, and integrals, and how they can be used to analyze and optimize business functions.

Throughout the course, students will learn how to use calculus to solve problems related to business functions such as revenue, cost, profit, and demand. They will also learn how to use calculus to analyze and optimize business processes such as production, inventory, and pricing.

In addition to theoretical concepts, this course will also provide practical applications of calculus in business. Students will work on case studies and real-world examples to develop their problem-solving skills and apply their knowledge to real-world scenarios.

By the end of this course, students will have a solid understanding of calculus and its applications in business. They will be able to use calculus to analyze and optimize business functions and processes, and make informed decisions based on mathematical analysis. This course will prepare students for advanced courses in business and economics, as well as for careers in finance, accounting, and management."

"""Course Description:

Contemporary Western Philosophy is a course designed for 2nd Year Applied English Students who are interested in exploring the philosophical ideas and concepts that have shaped the modern world. This course will provide students with an in-depth understanding of the major philosophical movements and thinkers of the 20th and 21st centuries, including existentialism, postmodernism, feminism, and critical theory.

Through a combination of lectures, readings, and discussions, students will examine the key philosophical questions that have emerged in the contemporary era, such as the nature of reality, the meaning of life, the role of language and communication, and the relationship between the individual and society. Students will also explore the ways in which these philosophical ideas have influenced other fields, such as literature, art, and politics.

By the end of the course, students will have developed a critical and analytical approach to philosophical texts and ideas, as well as an appreciation for the relevance of philosophy in contemporary society. They will also have honed their writing and communication skills through a series of assignments and presentations that require them to articulate their own philosophical perspectives and engage with the ideas of others.

Overall, Contemporary Western Philosophy is an engaging and challenging course that will provide students with a deeper understanding of the philosophical ideas that have shaped our world, and equip them with the skills and knowledge to engage with these ideas in a meaningful way."""

"""Course Description:

Advertising Marketing is a course designed for 3rd Year Information and Communication Students who are interested in learning about the principles and practices of advertising and marketing. This course will provide students with a comprehensive understanding of the advertising industry, including the different types of advertising, advertising strategies, and advertising campaigns.

Throughout the course, students will learn about the different marketing techniques used to promote products and services, including market research, target audience analysis, and branding. They will also explore the various advertising mediums, such as print, television, radio, and digital media, and how to create effective advertising campaigns for each medium.

The course will also cover the legal and ethical considerations of advertising, including advertising regulations, consumer protection laws, and advertising ethics. Students will learn how to create advertising campaigns that are both effective and ethical, and how to avoid common pitfalls in advertising.

By the end of the course, students will have a solid understanding of the advertising industry and the marketing techniques used to promote products and services. They will be able to create effective advertising campaigns that are both ethical and successful, and they will be prepared to enter the advertising industry with confidence."""

"Prompt Engineering for Creatives" is designed to equip 1st Year Marketing Students with the skills to craft effective prompts for AI-driven content creation tools. This course covers the fundamentals of prompt engineering, exploring how to generate engaging, brand-consistent content across various platforms. Students will learn techniques to optimize prompts for creativity, clarity, and audience engagement, while also understanding the ethical considerations in AI use. Through hands-on projects and real-world case studies, students will develop the ability to leverage AI to enhance their marketing strategies and drive innovative campaigns.

"Real-time Systems" is a foundational course for 1st grade master's students in Computer Science, focusing on the principles and practices of designing, implementing, and analyzing systems that respond to inputs within strict timing constraints. Students will explore topics such as real-time operating systems, scheduling algorithms, concurrency, and resource management. Through a combination of theoretical lectures and practical lab sessions, students will gain hands-on experience in developing and testing real-time applications. By the end of the course, students will be equipped with the skills to tackle real-world challenges in industries like automotive, aerospace, and telecommunications.
Course Details.Target Students: 1st grade master students for Computer Science

Course Details.Course Description: "Introduction to Artificial Intelligence" is a foundational course designed for 2nd Year Computer Science students, offering a comprehensive overview of AI principles and techniques. Students will explore key concepts such as machine learning, neural networks, natural language processing, and robotics. The course combines theoretical understanding with practical applications, including hands-on projects and coding assignments to build and evaluate AI models. By the end of the course, students will have a solid grasp of AI's capabilities, limitations, and ethical considerations, preparing them for advanced AI topics and real-world problem-solving. This course is part of the Generative AI series of courses of "Educational Applications of Generative Artificial Intelligence in Precision Health and Care"

"Big Data Analysis in Healthcare" is a specialized course designed for 4th Year Computer Science students, focusing on the application of big data technologies in the healthcare sector. Students will explore data collection, storage, processing, and analysis techniques specific to healthcare data, learning to handle diverse data types such as electronic health records, genomic data, and medical imaging. The course covers machine learning algorithms, data mining, and predictive analytics to uncover insights and improve patient outcomes. Practical projects and case studies will provide hands-on experience, preparing students for careers at the intersection of technology and healthcare.

"Artificial Intelligence in Healthcare" is an advanced course designed for 4th-year Computer Science students, focusing on the application of AI technologies within the healthcare sector. Students will explore machine learning, natural language processing, and computer vision techniques to address medical challenges such as diagnostics, personalized treatment, and predictive analytics. The course includes hands-on projects, case studies, and collaboration with healthcare professionals to develop practical solutions. By the end of the course, students will have a robust understanding of how AI can enhance patient care, streamline hospital operations, and contribute to medical research. This course is part of the Generative AI series courses of "Educational Applications of Generative Artificial Intelligence in Precision Health and Care"

Course Details.Course Title: Generative AI in Precision Healthcare Applications
Course Details.Course Description: "Generative AI in Precision Healthcare Applications" is an advanced course designed for 4th Year Computer Science students, focusing on the integration of generative AI techniques in personalized medicine. Students will explore AI-driven innovations in diagnostics, treatment planning, and patient-specific healthcare solutions. The curriculum covers deep learning, natural language processing, and bioinformatics, alongside ethical considerations and data privacy. Through hands-on projects and case studies, students will gain practical experience in developing AI applications that enhance precision healthcare, preparing them for cutting-edge roles in the intersection of technology and medicine. This course is part of the Generative AI series courses of "Educational Applications of Generative Artificial Intelligence in Precision Health and Care"

"Machine Learning" is an advanced course designed for 3rd Year Computer Science students, focusing on the theoretical foundations and practical applications of machine learning algorithms. Students will explore supervised and unsupervised learning, neural networks, and natural language processing. The course includes hands-on projects using popular frameworks like TensorFlow and scikit-learn, emphasizing problem-solving and real-world applications. By the end of the course, students will be equipped to design, implement, and evaluate machine learning models, preparing them for careers in AI, data science, and related fields. Prerequisites include a solid understanding of programming, statistics, and linear algebra. This course is part of the Generative AI series courses of "Educational Applications of Generative Artificial Intelligence in Precision Health and Care"

"Machine Learning" introduces 2nd Year Computer Science Students to the foundations and applications of machine learning algorithms. This course covers topics such as supervised and unsupervised learning, neural networks, and deep learning. Students will gain hands-on experience in implementing algorithms, analyzing data, and building predictive models. Emphasis is placed on understanding the theoretical concepts behind machine learning, as well as practical implementation in real-world scenarios. By the end of the course, students will be equipped with the knowledge and skills to tackle complex problems in artificial intelligence and data analysis using machine learning techniques.

"Machine Learning" introduces 1st-year students to the fundamentals of artificial intelligence and data analysis. This course covers key concepts such as algorithms, statistical modeling, and pattern recognition to teach students how machines can learn from data and make predictions. Through hands-on projects and practical applications, students will develop skills in programming, data manipulation, and model evaluation. By the end of the course, students will be equipped to understand and implement basic machine learning techniques, setting a strong foundation for further exploration in this rapidly growing field.

"LLM (Logic, Language, and Mathematics) is a dynamic course designed for 3rd-year BS Computer Science students. This course delves into the fundamental principles of logic, explores the intricacies of various programming languages, and applies mathematical concepts to problem-solving in computer science. Students can expect to enhance their critical thinking skills, deepen their understanding of programming languages, and strengthen their mathematical reasoning abilities. Through a combination of theoretical learning and practical application, LLM equips students with the essential tools and knowledge needed to excel in the ever-evolving field of computer science."

"人工智慧倫理" is a specialized course designed for fourth-year undergraduate and first and second-year master's students. This course delves into the ethical considerations surrounding artificial intelligence (AI), exploring topics such as privacy, bias, accountability, and the impact of AI on society. Course Details.Course Description: "Digital Image Processing and Applications" is a specialized course designed for 4th Year Electrical Engineering Students focusing on the fundamental principles and practical applications of processing digital images. Students will explore topics such as image enhancement, segmentation, feature extraction, and pattern recognition. Through hands-on projects and case studies, participants will develop skills in utilizing advanced software tools for image analysis and manipulation. This course equips students with the knowledge and techniques needed to tackle real-world challenges in fields like medical imaging, robotics, and remote sensing. Gain a deeper understanding of digital image processing and its diverse engineering applications in this dynamic course.
